subSubSection.paragraph:
Redescription. Male 
holotype
.

Body (
Figs. 21–22
) black with antennal club ventrally light-brown over black and dorsally black, 
14.8 mm
long, 
8.8 mm
wide across elytra post median. Mentum weakly reflexed at apex, bilobed with indistinct medial groove with ligula reflexed, apically attenuate with apex weakly bilobed.Antennal club (
Figs. 21–25
) only slightly longer than shaft, inner face setose, shallowly foveate on apical third; outer face of club bitexturous with ventral and dorsal portions subequal, club straight, in outline with ventral margin strongly bowed. Clypeus (
Figs. 21, 24–25
) attenuate with arcuate reflexed apex, abruptly declivous from broadly rounded ridge joining antennal angles, surface rugulose; clypeofrontal ridge distinct. Frons (
Figs. 21, 24–25
) rugulose; ocular canthi with anterior margin weakly arcuate, laterally truncate, anterior margin bearing long orange setae. Pronotum (
Figs. 21, 23–25
) with anterior lateral angles slightly obtuse, widest in anterior half, about one-third distance from anterior margin; anteromedian horn stout, erect, preceding a transverse impression confined to anterior third with abrupt posterior margin, basal convexity uninterrupted; surface sparsely and finely punctate, punctures becoming coarser, denser towards margins often transverse along anterolateral margins; simple punctures tending transverse in impression;, basal ridge complete. Scutellum (
Fig. 21
) with sparse moderate punctures medially in basal half. Each elytron (
Figs. 21, 23
) with sutural striae punctate to apex, elytral disc with small, shallow, umbilicate punctures forming well-defined striae, intervals with random punctures, punctures continuous to apical calli, lateral declivity sparsely rugulose. Pygidium (
Fig. 26
) moderately convex, weakly microreticulate, concentrically punctate, with dense long setae across base and sparsely punctate apical zone, apical ridge not thickened medially, bearing dense fringe of long setae across median third. Abdominal sternites 2–4 (
Fig. 22
) laterally setose over entire surface, last sternite bearing continuous fringe setae on posterior margin. Coxae (
Fig. 22
) bearing orange vestiture; metatibiae with basal carinae bearing long, acute setae, apical carinae bearing long, fine closely set ciliae on outer surface; metatibial spurs (
Fig. 22
) of unequal length, long, subparallel, with longer spur slightly curved. Genitalia as in 
Figs. 27–28
.

